I like the idea of keeping service mappings in the domain system.  I would
worry about host access to these databases, though.
We could distribute the network and server overhead of accessing them
by adding some more servers as Rob suggests.  But consider how dependent
hosts would become on these databases, and what would happen if some
network became isolated from the Internet.  Hosts can function without
remote DNS access but probably not without service&lt;-&gt;number mappings.

I think we'd probably want at least one secondary server for such a database on
practically every (logical) network in the Internet.  This doesn't seem
impractical to me, but the two order of magnitude increase in server count
would involve a different distribution scheme, e.g. a distribution tree
rather than a star centered on the NIC.

Adding a single new ANUM RR sounds easier to deal with than adding one
per OSI layer.

	Stuart

